Description: FSI International, Inc. designs, manufactures, markets, and supports equipment used in the fabrication of microelectronics, such as
Headquarters Regions: Greater Minneapolis-Saint Paul Area, Great Lakes, Midwestern US
Full Description: FSI International, Inc. designs, manufactures, markets, and supports equipment used in the fabrication of microelectronics, such as advanced semiconductor devices. The company provides surface conditioning technology solutions and microlithography systems, and support services to the manufacturers of integrated circuits. It manufactures, markets, and supports surface conditioning equipment that uses wet, cryogenic, and other chemistry techniques to clean, strip, or etch the surfaces of silicon wafers, and supplies refurbished microlithography products that are used to deposit and develop light sensitive films. The company offers system and subsystem upgrade packages, spare part kits, individual spare part components, robot refurbishment and replacement, and support services that provide product and process enhancements to extend the life of previously purchased and installed systems. It also sells various process, service, and maintenance programs. FSI International, Inc. markets its products to the manufacturers of microelectronic devices worldwide. The company was founded in 1973 and is based in Chaska, Minnesota.

Description: Optimizing human performance by creating a constant feedback loop between trainers and their athletes' muscles
Headquarters Regions: East Coast, Southern US
Full Description: Our vision is to create a deep understanding of human movement that unlocks potential within performance and rehabilitation. We do this by transforming gigabytes of movement data into key, practical insights that any sport scientist, coach, or physical therapist can easily use to guide decision making.  At the moment, we focus on uncovering insights within muscle activity data. Before, there was always a tradeoff between speed of analysis and depth of insights. This limited the potential of muscle activity data in practical applications.  We’ve uncovered a way to speak to the muscles and get in depth information into specificity, intensity, and volume of training straight from the source of performance.  Instead of proxies for internal load, we get data straight from the muscles. This reduces the margin of error of training assumptions by ~30%.  Then, we quantify and visualize training stimulus and fatigue so that coaches can rapidly test assumptions and adapt their programs to their athletes’ needs.  Coaches can now create a constant feedback loop between them and their athletes’ muscles to catch risky actions before they affect performance, or worse, lead to injury.
